Alright, to replicate the design and functionality of this product page in a Next.js React app, we'll break it down step by step. Let's start with the CSS. I'll be assuming that you have a basic understanding of how to set up a Next.js app. If not, the official Next.js documentation is a great place to start.

### 1. CSS for the product page:

For this project, I'll be using a combination of `styled-jsx` (which comes built-in with Next.js) and regular CSS to style the components.

```css
/* styles.css */
body {
    font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif; /* This is just an example, you'd replace this with whatever font you're using */
    background-color: #F5F5F5;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

.header {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    padding: 20px 50px;
}

.product-content {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 50px auto;
    padding: 20px;
    background-color: #FFFFFF;
}

.product-title {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: bold;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.product-price {
    font-size: 20px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.product-options {
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.product-description {
    font-size: 14px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.product-buttons {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
}

.footer {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 50px 0;
}

```

### 2. Setting up the Next.js app:

First, create a new Next.js app:

```bash
npx create-next-app product-page
```

Navigate to your project directory:

```bash
cd product-page
```

Now, let's create the product page.

### 3. Create the product page component:

Here's an example of how the product page component might look:

```jsx
// pages/index.js
import React from 'react';
import '../styles.css';

const ProductPage = () => {
    return (
        <div className="product-content">
            <h1 className="product-title">MATHESON BATH SHEET</h1>
            <p className="product-price">$130.00 NZD</p>
            <div className="product-options">
                <label>
                    <input type="radio" name="option" value="individual" />
                    Individual
                </label>
                <label>
                    <input type="radio" name="option" value="pair" />
                    Pair
                </label>
            </div>
            <p className="product-description">
                100% Organic Cotton bath sheet with a luxuriously soft handle. Reminiscent of heritage club rooms, Matheson is generous in size and defined by textural moss rib accented by three crème stripes. Inspired by the spaces where an individual sits, inwardly connected to, the post-match exhale.
            </p>
            <div className="product-buttons">
                <button>-</button>
                <button>Add to Cart</button>
                <button>+</button>
            </div>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ProductPage;
```

This is a basic example. You would need to integrate additional functionality for selecting product options, adjusting quantity, and adding to cart. For fonts, you would probably want to import a custom font (e.g., via Google Fonts or similar) to match the one in the image more closely.

Remember to update your CSS and your components as you see fit to make them match the provided image. This is just a starting point to help guide you in setting up a product page in Next.js with React.
